efending national territory and independence, but has seen offensive military power as ineffective for promoting other goals-such as suppressing terrorist networks and WMD proliferation, or promoting democracy overseas. Over several decades, these realist attitudes have become more evident as the Japanese state has gradually convinced its public that Tokyo and its military can be trusted with territorial defense, and even with noncombat humanitarian and reconstruction missions overseas. On this basis, says Midford, we should re-conceptualize Japanese public opinion as attitudinal defensive realism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aJapan - Military policy - Public opinion. 0aJapan -- Military policy -- Public opinion. 0aNational security - Japan - Public opinion. 0aNational security -- Japan -- Public opinion. 0aNational securityxPublic opinionxJapan. 0aNational securityzJapanxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinion - Japan. 0aPublic opinion -- Japan. 0aPublic opinionxJapan. 0aPublic opinionzJapan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477771140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777711.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles